{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537003"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:12:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:12:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15852"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15852"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.47,0.2,0.17,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8543"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62874"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8543"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15852"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48324"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1329"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20496"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38715"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62874"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with three months of progressive exertional dyspnoea and bilateral ankle swelling. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes, hypertension, and obesity with a BMI of 34 kg/m\u00b2. Her medications include metformin, amlodipine, and perindopril. On examination, she appears mildly short of breath. Her pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 146/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There is bilateral pitting oedema to the mid-shin. Heart sounds are dual with no murmurs. Chest examination reveals fine bibasal crackles. An echocardiogram shows normal left ventricular systolic function with an ejection fraction of 62%, but evidence of diastolic dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications would be most likely to reduce future hospital admissions in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Metoprolol","Empagliflozin","Furosemide","Spironolactone","Hydrochlorothiazide"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of heart failure with preserved ejection fraction (HFpEF), characterised by symptoms of heart failure despite normal left ventricular systolic function. The presence of risk factors including obesity, hypertension, and diabetes is typical for HFpEF.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmpagliflozin\u003C/strong\u003E, a sodium-glucose cotransporter-2 (SGLT-2) inhibitor, has been shown in large clinical trials to significantly reduce hospitalisation rates in patients with heart failure, regardless of ejection fraction or the presence of diabetes. The EMPEROR-Preserved trial demonstrated that empagliflozin reduced the combined risk of cardiovascular death or hospitalisation for heart failure in patients with HFpEF.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E is commonly used for symptom relief in heart failure but has not been shown to reduce mortality or hospitalisation rates. While it helps manage fluid overload, it does not address the underlying pathophysiology of HFpEF.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrochlorothiazide\u003C/strong\u003E may help with blood pressure control and mild fluid retention but has not been shown to significantly impact hospitalisation rates in heart failure patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E and other beta-blockers, while beneficial in heart failure with reduced ejection fraction, have not demonstrated significant benefits in reducing hospitalisations specifically in HFpEF.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpironolactone\u003C/strong\u003E has shown some benefit in selected patients with HFpEF, particularly in the TOPCAT trial, but the evidence for reducing hospitalisations is not as robust as for SGLT-2 inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["SGLT-2 inhibitors reduce hospitalisation rates in patients with heart failure regardless of ejection fraction.","Heart failure with preserved ejection fraction (HFpEF) commonly presents with exertional dyspnoea and peripheral oedema.","Obesity, hypertension, and diabetes are common risk factors for HFpEF."],"references":["2022 AHA/ACC/HFSA Guideline for the Management of Heart Failure: A Report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Joint Committee on Clinical Practice Guidelines"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48324"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15852"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48324"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-19T07:57:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-19T07:58:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8543"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62874"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":